Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada (also referred to as "Bhaktivedanta Swami" or "Prabhupada"), a Gaudiya Vaishnava sannyasi and teacher, arrived in New York City from his native India in 1965 and "caught the powerful rising tide" of a counterculture that was fascinated with his homeland and open to new forms of "consciousness-expanding spirituality."[14] After establishing his first American temple in New York City at 26Â Second Avenue, Prabhupada requested his early follower Mukunda Das[15][nb 1] and his wife Janaki Dasi to open a similar ISKCON center on the West Coast of the United States.[16][17][18]
